        <h1>4. <%= @your_option_page_title_4 %></h1>
      </header>

      <p>
        You can move your pension pot into a fund that allows you to take money out when you need it.
        This is called '<span class="tooltip" title="Your pension pot stays invested and you take money out when you need it">income drawdown</span>'. Ask your pension provider how to do this.
      </p>

      <p>
        The money will be re-invested and your fund could still grow. This depends on how well
        your investments do. Where your money is invested is up to you. You can use an Independent
        Financial Adviser (IFA) to advise you, or decide yourself.
      </p>

      <p>
        You then tell your pension provider when you need money and how much. They’ll pay it into
        your bank account after having taken off any <a href="/tax-on-your-pension/1">Income Tax</a> due.
      </p>

      <p>
        With <span class="tooltip" title="Your pension pot stays invested and you take money out when you need it">income drawdown</span> you can’t pay into your fund anymore. You’ll also pay charges to your
        pension provider to run the <span class="tooltip" title="Your pension pot stays invested and you take money out when you need it">income drawdown</span> fund for you.
      </p>

